Can the euro be saved?
Paris — German Finance Minister Schäuble recently put the option of Greece leaving the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state is exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a major discussion about the principles underlying the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal was put forward, European leaders had already taken note of the report on the future of the euro written by Commission President Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate about Greece has led many decision-makers to feel the need to return to the original starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency?
Does this make sense? Can there be agreement on Greece's future?
Currency is like a nation, and establishing it requires mythology.
Traditional wisdom sees the euro as the political price Germany paid to France for re-unification.
In fact, German re-unification was merely the final step of an initiative that had already taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing issue.
European governments strongly oppose floating exchange rates, seeing them as incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they are unwilling to maintain the monetary system dominated by the German central bank for a long period.
A genuine European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In retrospect, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in severe difficulties; France was undervalued and its economy was thriving.
Over the following decade, imbalances gradually emerged between the resurgent Germany and the countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would become without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark still be overvalued?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reform be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analysis baseline to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is by no means a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has consistently underperformed, and its political system must be held accountable for this.
What really matters is whether the common European currency will still be important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and if the eurozone disintegrates during a crisis, and exacerbates mutual conflict among member states, the costs would further increase).
Moreover, abolishing the euro could unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke from the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this argument is insufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting a couple should keep their marriage going just because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that monetary union would promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
On the contrary, internal trade and investment growth within the eurozone have been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further than the monetary unification, building the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the power they still have.
This may be politically logical, but economically it is useless: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, and thus we must never waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hope that the euro becomes one of the major international currencies (particularly considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy frameworks).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been largely fulfilled.
The international use of the euro is second only to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an insignificant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) believe that the institutions underlying the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the European level of policy is inherently higher than the national level.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, resulting in a poorer performance compared to the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy and institutional reforms must be implemented.
But the formulation and implementation of a schedule require a broad consensus on the nature of the problem.
Yet the ongoing debates over the Greek issue indicate that Europe is still far from reaching consensus: member states have conflicting analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, leading to conflicting remedies.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was significantly hindered by differing transmission patterns across countries.
Countries prefer joint action, but cannot agree on a consistent plan because they disagree on how diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this issue is not unsolvable, as evidenced by major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the initiation of a banking union.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, which demonstrates the importance of institutional governance.
However, the fact that reforms and actions have only recently begun and were implemented under severe crisis pressure makes us clearly aware of the difficulty in reaching consensus.
The eurozone can no longer delay or pretend.
The eurozone member states must establish a consistent agenda on governance and political reforms to turn the monetary union into an engine of prosperity; otherwise, they will sink into repeated debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reforms.
Now, all major stakeholders have an obligation to clarify what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to trade in exchange for what they want.
